No, the separation between the two isn't about the availability of magic or the fact it's well known or not. It's more a question of how great-and-powerful/fairy-tale-ish it is vs how realistic it is.

In high fantasy the poor people aren't starving and dying due to bubonic plague and syphilis. Hell, they usually don't even make it on camera.

In low fantasy the world is much more realistic and gritty. I've seen some argument that 'low fantasy is set in a real world setting variant of our own world' but that doesn't match the way the term has been used to classify fiction in the past. I.E., Thieves World has traditionally been called LF but it sure as fuck isn't our world.

Yeah, the explanation is always kind of hard. On the face of it, I don't mind Trek-esque space cats. It's fiction. We know it's fiction. Space cats exist as a trope because we can easily imagine what space cats might be like. Overall, your aliens should serve the story. In something like Trek the point is that the aliens are very human-like because they represent aspects of humanity. You couldn't do Klingons if you'd first have to filter them through 3 translators and their culture was unfathomable. Trek is also full of physiologically radically different aliens, and often uses their biology to make its point. Such as subverting the monster in space trope with the Horta, or Q fucking around with the crew. For certain subgenres of science fiction we wouldn't blink twice at humanoid aliens.

Though, one idea I had for a setting does nab a little from Charles Stross's first work (I think Stross is a massive cunt, but his first book was OK). Ridiculously advanced aliens come along and fuck with humanity. They take some people and seed them across the galaxy, they also either uplift animals, or make some humans more like animals. Maybe both. No-one knows. Generally assumed to be their commentary on mankind's treatment of the natural world. Then, at some point, either FTL technology is spread by the aliens, or mankind discovers it for themselves, and all the different colonies start interacting again like the weird, diaspora space empires they are, with their own reactions and interpretations to the event.

And somewhere in all the chaos, there's some guy who thinks space cat ears are the softest thing ever.

Anonymous Fri 16 Nov 2018 19:58:56 No.19466430 Report

It's not just the focus of the camera.

In a lot of high fantasy settings it's like there ARE no poor people, no diseases (except magical weapon diseases created by evil overlords), and if there were no evil the world would be shiny and pretty and everyone would sing along with their local tweeting birds before breakfast. There's no place for the camera to focus EXCEPT pretty things better than the world we live in.

In low fantasy, you can tell he's a king because he ain't got shit on him.

Now it's usually not a perfect thing. For example: Tolkien's elves and dwarves are VERY high fantasy, but his humans and orcs are more low fantasy-ish. Industrialization, filth, betrayal, no concept of beauty.

Another thing that often divides:
High fantasy showcases ultimate good vs. ultimate evil. Galadriel vs. Sauron, while in low fantasy you don't find anything except a shit-ton of shades of grey.

High fantasy heroes slay the evil demon and the world is renewed and made a better place, and people sing songs of his glory for centuries to come. Low fantasy heroes sell their souls and live in eternal misery to prevent the demon from hurting the people they care about, and no one knows about his horrible sacrifice.

Star Wars is high fantasy in space, not science fiction. Firefly is low fantasy in a space western, not science fiction.

>>19466141
The line between high and low fantasy really just boils down to a checklist of story elements. They're more commonly used to neatly fit sub-genres under an umbrella, like urban fantasy and steampunk (with magic). High fantasy will generally have a setting unique to its world, as well as distinct races/sapient life forms, cultures, languages, nuances, etc. Low fantasy will usually lack a few of those things, but is more commonly used to categorize stories with some of those elements, but a realistic setting. LotR (set in midieval Midgard, or Middle Earth) is unironically a sound example of high fantasy; Jim Butcher's "Skin Game" (urban; set in early 20th century Chicago) is an example of low fantasy. Netflix's "Bright" also falls into the urban fantasy genre and is, itself, an example of low fantasy.
